Happy Labor Day weekend! So just a few thoughts on software as we close up the summer, and we also provide a few thoughts into HUBS' analyst day next week. While it was a rough August in software, the reaction to strong results from SNOW and MDB (not covered) provides a bit of a tailwind for the software bull case as we head into the fall. While the 'AI eats software' narrative is an effective short thesis when there is no 'beat/raise' momentum in the space or estimates are not going up, what SNOW and MDB illustrated is that reacceleration stories in software can drag investors off the sidelines. This aligns with other YTD winners like MSFT or ORCL where acceleration in Azure and OCI has helped drive shares higher. Essentially, software is a huge space so applying a blanket short narrative for the entire sector does not make a ton of sense and the infra names are clearly seeing more benefits from AI vs. apps at this point. Along those lines, CRM earnings on Weds night will be an interesting litmus test for the apps names as expectations are low and the valuation is arguably washed out. However, with Dreamforce on the horizon and the potential for revenue to reaccelerate in 2H (more likely F4Q), if CRM shares can hang in at these levels following 'slight beat/keep' F2Q results, that could signal the start of a move back into select apps names or at least the start of a more tradable bottom. It's worth noting WDAY is up relative to where it was on T+1 post F2Q EPS.

Bottom line: We would caution in terms of over extrapolating SNOW/MDB's results relative to the rest of software, but their T+1 moves speak to: 1) investors will reward clean beat/raise results; 2) revenue reacceleration = multiple expansion and this is still a possibility of 2H reacceleration for CRM, HUBS, and WDAY; and 3) the apathy towards software can shift quickly and if money flow returns to the space, there could be some material upside for select names in C4Q. Enjoy the long weekend!

For our weekly catalyst note this week, we wanted to share some thoughts ahead of HubSpot's Inbound user conference & Analyst Day next Wednesday in SF. We also thought HUBS' co- founder and CTO Dharmesh Shah's blog on the 'AI eats software' discussion was notable and a very reasonable take on the interplay between apps and AI when thinking out a few years. Please see inside for more details.

We believe HUBS' analyst day will largely revolve around the Gen Al innovation that the company has been bringing to market over the last year, including Breeze Intelligence as well as some of the early agents (Customer, Prospecting, and Content). While the 'up to \(5\%\) price hike is expected to start impacting the financials in a more meaningful way in F4Q (as a larger portion of customers that have been migrated will be up for renewal), we expect the more interesting topic as it relates to potential revenue acceleration will involve any color in terms of consumption revenue contribution from these Agents as well as data enrichment via Breeze Intelligence as customers look to unify their data more holistically in the Gen Al world. Worth noting also that we expect that the company will address 'head on' the recent bear thesis of 'SaaS is dead' that has weighed on horizontal application software YTD - interesting post on the topic from Founder and CTO Dharmesh Shah a couple weeks ago.

From a financial perspective, will be interested to see if any update to the current medium/longer term margin guides (FY26 18- 20%, FY27 20- 22%, LT 25%) given the progress towards these targets over the last 3 years (current FY25 guide of \(\sim 18\%\) implies \(+300\) bps expansion over the last 2 years) as well as the fact that the company is leaning into Gen Al fairly heavily. Aside from that, expect the standard discussions around TAM updates, multi- hub adoption, \(\%\) of customers moving upmarket with larger deals, etc.

Bottom line: While we are expecting an upbeat discussion around Gen Al/Breeze and any bump to the margin guides would be a notable positive, we continue to believe that the bigger potential 're- rate' is likely going to be on the F3Q call as investors have insight into whether the combination of the 'up to \(5\%\) price hikes + any early consumption revenue contribution can lead to a reacceleration in revenue growth. We continue to believe that this is a distinct possibility given the 1H constant currency outperformance ( \(\sim 300\) bps in 1Q, \(\sim 200\) bps in 2Q) coupled with the fact that compares continue to ease in the 2H, despite the fact that the current guidance of \(\sim 17\%\) implies a couple points of 2H deceleration.

Below, we simply offer some of the standard metrics that we would expect to see. Tougher to know if management will be willing to offer up any metrics in terms of Agentic contribution, though any positive indicators on the front would likely be well- received from investors that are looking to dimensionalize the likelihood of seeing revenue reacceleration into the 2H and potentially into FY26 - as the 26% growth mark remains a key 'optical differentiator' for investors evaluating a large software landscape.
Figure 1: Expect that management will offer an update on the TAM opportunity, likely reflective of Agents becoming a larger part of the software business model.
Source: Company Data, Evercore ISI Research

Figure 2: We would expect an update in terms of growth on an individual Hub level, with Sales having come up in some of our recent partner surveys as showing some momentum. Given some of the recent concerns around SEO, seeing continued durability in Marketing Hub growth would also be helpful - Marketing Hub momentum also took a nice q/q step up in our most recent survey.
Source: Company Data, Evercore ISI Research

Figure 3: As HubSpot continues to look to move higher up in the market, multi-hub adoption and deal sizes getting larger remains a key focus point. We would expect an update on the progress that the company is making on that front.
Source: Company Data, Evercore ISI Research

Figure 4: Multi-hub adoption/moving upmarket is a key driver of platform 'stickiness' and as such we will be interested to see that gross retention metric continue to evolve over time. While the SMB exposure will likely limit gross retention from ever reaching ServiceNow-esque levels of 98-99%, expect that shifting north of 90% would be a nice milestone. Additionally, with a larger portion of customers now 'right-sized' in terms of 'core seats', seeing NRR start to shift higher into CY26 will be key for unlocking a 're-rating' in the shares.
Source: Company Data, Evercore ISI Research

Figure 5: While we believe any firm targets regarding top-line/Agentic contribution are unlikely, expect that given the continued progress towards the medium and longer term op. margin targets, seeing an update (perhaps \(25\%\) by FY28 with a \(-30\%\) LT guide?) would be viewed as a key positive indicator for investors.
Source: Company Data, Evercore ISI Research
